{"/service/ndnp/arhi/batch_arhi_dioptase_ver02/data/sn92050145/00516990351/1930112101/0744.xml":{"full_text":"bringing Yon Official Labor Nawa That\nYon Can Get Only Through Your\nLabor Paper.\nLabor\nBulletin\nArkansas* Official Labor l\u2019ublication\nReaching the Best=Paid Class of\nPeople as a Whole in the State,\nVOL. XXXIL No. 47.\nLITTLE ROCK. ARKANSAS, NOVEMBER 21, 1980\nFIVE CENTS\nJLabor Wins the Be^t Congress\nSince 1912, Morrison Asserts\nVOTING ENLARGED FRIENDLY\nv GROUPS IN BOTH HOUSES\nSenate Supporters of Judge Parker Defeated and Men Who\nStood With Labor Re-elected Senator Norris\nAn Easy Victor.\nLabor scored heavy victories in the recent national elec\ntions. retiring to private life some additional members of the\nSenate who voted for Parker and generally enlarging the for\nward wedge in the Senate and House, from a purely non\npartisan viewpoint.\nIn the absence of President\nGreen, Secretary Frank Morrison\nof the American Federation of La\nbor described the newly-elected\ncongress as \u201cthe most friendly\nsipce the first Wilson administra\ntion,\u201d and this verdict seemed to\nexpress the general feeling of all\ntrade union leaders.\nSome new pro-labor faces will be\nseen, in the new congress.\nAmong the outstanding labor\nachievements was the defeat of i\nSenator Boscoe C. McCullough, Ke- j\npublican, of Ohio, who was one of\nthe leading supporters of Judge\nParker in that famous battle.\nAnother ardent Parker supporter\nsent down to defeat was Senator j\nHenry J. Allen, Kepublican, Kan\nsas, Other pro-Parker senators\ndisappeared earlier, Phipps of\nColorado having declined to run,\nwhile Simmons of North Carolina,\nwas beaten in the primaries. Hleas\nof South Carolina, and Ransdel! of\nLouisiana, were also beaten in the\nprimaries.\nInterest in the victories of\nfriends easily centered in the vet\neran Norris of Nebraska, and\nWalsh of Montana. Norris woo a\nhandsome victory over a series of\namazing moves. It is interesting\nti oaje that while Norris wp;, Con\ngressman Carroll Reese, Tennes\nsee, chairman of the House sub\ncommittee which had the Norris\nMuscle Shoals bill in charge, and\nwhich blocked that bill, went down\nin defeat. If power was an issue\nin Tennessee and in Nebraska, it\nalso was an issue in New York,\nwhere Franklin D. Roosevelt, en-'\ndersed by labor, piled up a record\n(Continued on page j\nby Arthur Brisbane\nThe Five-Day Week\nLadendorff Sees War\nHunting the Microbe\nOne Billion Ounces\nPaul Mazur of the firm of Leh\nman Brothers says the five-day j\nweek should be adopted universal-!\nly, to concentrate working, selling\nand buying in five days, giving\neverybody two days to spend what\nthey earn in health and efficiency.\nSuch a plan, according to Mr.\nMazur, would encourage spending\nand increase baying at Least 20 per\ncant.\nThe alump in employment should\nconvince the feeble-minded that\nkeeping out immigration docs not\n\"guarantee steady work for every\nbody in the United States.\"\nTo guarantee steady work you\nneed buyers for goods produced,\nand to increase the buying you\nmust increase the purchasing pop\nulation.\nif this country had 50.000,000\nmore population of the right kind\nit would be 50 per cent better off\nin every way.\nGeneral Ludendorff sees another\nwar in 1932. When it is over, ac- j\ncording to his prophecy, \"Germany\nand Italy will be crushed. Russia,\nEngland and Austria will side with\nGermany, but France, heading an\nother group, will win\nTiiat prophecy need noi no taken\naetWKy. The German generals\nnad little idea of what was going\nto happen in 1914. They counted on\na single victorious campaign to last\na few months.\ns*\nJJan'g occupation from the be\nginning has been hunting down his\nenemies to destroy them, or hunt\ner other men and animals for\nj,Hunters at first used their own'\n(Continued on Page 5) i\nSTREET RAILWAY\nAUXILIARY PLANS\nCHRISTMAS PARTY\nBy Mrs. W. D. Lively, Corresp.\nThe Ladies\u2019 Society to the Street\nRailway Employes No. 704, held an\nall day meeting at the home of\nMrs. L. R. Thrash, Wednesday, No\nvember 12.\nAt noon a covered dish luncheon\nwas served and a large attendance\nparticipated.\nIn the afternoon, the business\nsession was called to order by the\nvice president, Mrs. J. A. Jeffries,\nwho officiated in the absence of\nthe president.\nMany important issues were dis\ncussed and acted upon, but the\nmain issue of the day was the\nplanning of a Christmas party. It\nwas decided to convene at the\nhome of Mrs. A. D. Valentin\u00ae, 4216\nWest Eleventh street, Dec. 10.\nAll members of the society are\nuiged to be present. Many gifts\nwill be awarded and none should\nfaii to be present for they are like\nly to miss either a splendid time\nor d nice present, according io the\nlodge\u2019s correspondent.\nRAILWAYS RESIST\nSTATE WAGE LAW\nAlbany, N. Y. The State Su- j\npreme Court, next month, will pass\non the plea of eight railroads to\nset aside the state legislature\u2019s act\ncompelling railroads to observe\nthe eight-hour day and \u201cthe pre\nvailing rate of wages on all grade\ncrossing work.\nThe elimination of grade cross\nings will cost $300,000,000, euqally\ndivided between the railroads and\nthe state. At a time when every\none agrees that high purchasing\npower fill relieve unemployment,\nthe railroads seek the right to\nlower wages on the ground that\nthis work is a private venture and\nis not subject to state regulation.\nThe case will eventually find its\nway to the United States Supreme\nCourt. It is one of the biggest law\nsuits New York state ever faced.\nThe railroads that have joined\nin the fight against the law are\nthe Ne\\v York Central, Delawa***.\nHudson, Long Island, Lackawanna,\nErie, Lehigh Valley, New Haven\nand Staten Island Rapid Transit.\nCHEMISTS PREDICT\nSILK FROM WATER GAS\nNew York. Artificial silk out\nof the abundant supply of natural\nwater gas by means of high pres\nsure hydrogenation was predicted\nby Dr. Per K. Frolieh of the re\nsearch staff of the Standard Oil\nCompany of New Jersey. The new\nsilk, said Dr. Frolieh, will more\nclosely resemble the natural prod\nuct than rayon.\n\u201cIn pressure,\u201d continued Dr.\nFrolieh, \"the chemist has discover\ned a tool with which he is now\nrapidly opening up a new field of\nindustrial activity. There is no\nchemical reason why dyestuffs\nshould not be produced out of the\nabundant supply of natural water\ngaa b ybuilding thef up through\nthe addition of hydrogen under\nhigh pressure. In the same manner\nwe should be able to produce syn\nthetic fats and proteins from water\ngas.\u201d\nMOVIE OPERATORS WIN\nMinneapolis.\u2014Movie picture op\nerators won a lockout that several\nl-uai theater, enforced 18 weeks\nTRAINMEN AND\nAUXILIARIES FORM\nSTATE BODY\n\nAnother step for promotion and\nidvancement was made by the\nL'rotherhood of Railroad Train\nrun and auxiliaries Thursday Oc\ntober 30 ,1930. when representa\ntives of both organizations\nthroughout the state met in the W.!\nO. W. hall. Little Rock, Ark., to j\ndiscuss the birth of a state organ-1\nNation to help boost and promote 1\nj their welfare and interests.\nMr. M. P. Parker of Little Rock,\npusided at the meeting pro tern,\nand Mrs. J. L. Cobb acted as sec\nretary, the former outlining the\nplans and purpose of the meeting,\nwhich read in part as'follows:\n\u201cIt shall convene in such cities\na\u00ab the organizations see fit to meet\nin. Its aim and purpose shall be\nto unite the several lodges of the\nbrotherhood of Railroad Trainmen\nand Ladies* Auxiliaries in the state\nof Arkansas for the promotion of\ntheir general welfare and advance\nment of the social, moral and in\ntellectual interest in the principle\nof conservative organized labor\nwhich will derive from a closer af\nfiliation, believing this a mutual\nbenefit to both organizations and\niii accordance with the laws and\npolicies of these organizations, this\nmeeting is being organized.\u2019*\nThis year a state meeting was\nheld in Pine Bluff at which Mrs.\nClara Bradley, grand president of\nthe Ladies Society to the Railroad\nTrainmen, addressed the members,\nand another similar meeting this\nyear in Little Rock, was planned.\nThe newly organized body waa\nnamed \u201cThe Arkansas Joint State\nAssociation\u201d and its first object\nwill be to help make the state\nmeeting to convene in Little Rock\nnext, year, a decided success. The\nfollowing officers were elected:\nMr M. P. Parker, general chair\nman; Mrs. C. E. Mitchell, general\nvice chairman; Mrs. J. L. Cobb,\nsecretary; Mrs. R. W. Harris,\ntreasurer; Mr. T. A. Redd In (of\nFine Bluff), chaplain, and Mr. H.\nC. Maleom, chairman of committee\non Arrangements.\nWhile the state meeting in Pine\nLhiff tliis year was pronounced a\nsuccess, with the aid of the Arkan\nsas Joint State Association another\nyear, the state meeting should far!\nexceed any precious meeting ever\nsponsored in this state by the,\ntrainmen, their auxiliaries, and\nthe above officers will have the j\nhonor and distinction of helping!\nsteer\u201d it to success.\nNo Wage Slashes Says\nGeneral Motors Chief\nNew York.\u2014Alfred P. Sloan Jr.\ni president of General Motors-, told\nnis stockholders last we\u00a3k that\nthere must be no reduction of the\nwage scale. j\n\u201cThe prosperity of the United,\nSmtes is founded on a high wage\nsrfle,\u201d he said, \u201cand it is import-!\nant that industry should appreciate j\nthat fact.\u201d\nI Machine at Root of Idleness, federal\nReserve Board Shows By Statistics\nBank Figures in Graphic Chart Shows Production in Gain in Volume, While the Number of Employed Fell in Ten Years\nIndustrial production 'has in-1\nj creased every _year since 1921,\n[\"'bile every single year, without\nexception, has witnessed a decrease\nin the number of wage earners em\nployed.\nThese are Federal Reserve Board\nfigures, backing up organized la\ntor\u2019s contention officially and with\ni statistics.\nThe Federal Resene Board of\nfers no explanation of its figures\u2014\nit does not explain how production\nincreases while numbers of per\nsons on pay roll* decrease. It sets\nforth the figures which teil more\neloquently than oratory of the\nsteady stream of workers thrown\naf'de to make way for automatic\nmachinery.\nThe figures, as charted by Ralph\nF. Coach, statistician and analyst,\nSTREET CAR MAN\nGETS PLEASANT\nBIRTHDAY SURPRISE\nBy Mrs. W. D. Lively, Correa.\nMr. Dave Howe of this city, re\nceived the surprise of. his life, Sun\nday November 9, when he return\ned from a stroll in the country, ac\ncompanied by his nephews (which\nhad been carefully planned by Mrs.\nRcwe) and found a large congre\ngation of friends there to help him\ncelebrate his birthday.\nMr. Howe was very generous to\nthe Ladies* Society of .the Street\nbail way Employes in the summer\nand gave much time and effort in\npreparing their float for the Labor\nI Day parade. The sdciety expressed\nits gratitude in the form of a\nI birthday party.\nApproximately 40 people were\npresent and a chicken dinaer was\nserved. Mrs. W. W. Thompson had\nthe honor of baking the birthday j\ntake. While no candles were allow\ned to be placed on the cake, it is\nestimated that Mr. Howe is well,\nftst 21. He was showered with!\npresents.\n8 HOURS FOR WOMEN\nNOT GENERAL RULE\nWashington.\u2014The vast majority\nof women work more than eight\nhours, according to a statement is\nsued by the United States Women\u2019s\nEureau. Contrary to general belief,\nwage-working women have no\neight-hour day, it is stated.\n\"With the trend toward the five\nday week and suggestions of the\n;iux-hou( day, the eight-hour stand\nard is getting to be almost as old\u25a0\nfashioned as a 1920 automobile,\u201d i\nthe bureau states. I\n\u201cMany women in factories have\nar. eight-hour day or less, but they\nconstitute the minority of all those\nin industry, Uncle Sam\u2019s investi\ngations show. A work day of such\nlength was reported for only one\nfifth- of the 227,000 women work\ni ing in 2,700 factories, stores and\nlaundries scattered throughout. 16\nstates that were included in Wom\ncn\u2019s Bureau studies durin gthe pe\nj ricd 1919-1928.\"\n__\nRED TAPE IS IGNORED\nBY SECRETARY HURLEY\nWashington.\u2014Secretary of War\nHurley announces that his depart\nment will aid in meeting the unem\nployment situation by the issuance\nof all available cots and blankets\nto \u201crelieve conditions of-acute dis\ntress\u201d.\nThe secretary has no legal au\nthority for such action, but 'ne per\nsonally assumes responsibility for\nissuing this equipment.\nMOLDERS VICTIMIZED\nMorris, III.\u2014The Coleman Man\nufacturing Company repudiated its\nagreement with organized molders.\nThe company makes \u201cstop\u2019\u2019 and\n\u2019\u2019go\u2019\u2019 light bases for the city of\nChicago.\nshow thr.t the present great wave\nof unemployment begin is leer\nage as 1019, proceeding steadily\nand with growing volume up to the\npresent.\nIn his -weekly analysis of indus\ntrial conditions for International\nLabor New* Service and this news\npaper, Couch siys:\n\"Employment reached a peak in\n1920,' w hich', according to the index\nof the Federal Reserve Board has\nnot yet been equaled, despite the\nmultiplicatio nof production. One\nhundred and one persona were on\nfactory pay rolls in 1920 for each\nS3 at work in 1929, and for each\n97 at work in 1923. These are the\nyears of greatest manufactory ac\ntivity.\n\u201cIndustrial activity roae to ita\nhighest pja\u00a3 in 1929 when otj^pijt\nEDITORIAL\nOrganized Labor Will Stand By Our Institutions!\nWe have just witnessed the greatest collapse of finan\ncial institutions ever occurring in the history of the state\nWhile it is hoped many of the institutions will re-open, the\nfact remains that it is a blow to the financial and business\nstability of any state to have one-fourth of its banks, in\ncluding the largest financial institution in the state, sus\npend business.\nOf course, the collapse of the American Exchange and\nits member banks as well as the closing of several other\nsmall independent banks was not due to any unsoundness\nin the basic structure of Arkansas.\nThe hysteria brought on by the collapse of Caldwell\nand Company of Nashville, which was remotely connected\nwith these Arkansas institutions, was the direct cause of\nthe run on the American Exchange Bank of buttle Bock.\nThe fact that this bank could stand the withdrawal of\nsome four million dollars in cash was proof enough that it\nhad ample cash reserves. But even the mightiest oaks will\ncrack and splinter in the storm of a panic.\nBut we wohder after all if this is not just a lesson to\nus. The matter of chain banking and branch banking right\nnow is taking the spotlight in the financial discussions of\nthe nation. It is coming up for more discussion. There\nare advantages and disadvantages. One of the advantages\nis that a branch bank has the protection of a strong central\nbank. One of the difficulties is exemplified in the collapse\nof the Banks chain where all closed when the parent bank\ngot into difficulty. To us it seems a good time for some\nthorough study on our banking laws and in the conduct of\nour banking institutions.\nOrganized Labor in Arkansas long ago went on record\nfor a sound Bank Guaranty Law. In times like this we\nrealize the need for some such measure. The tragedy rf\nseeing the savings of men, women and children swept away\nin a wave of excitement such as has swept the state in re\ncent days is proof enough that something should be done.\nOrganized Labor has always stood by Arkansas banks.\nThey are standing by now. They will support the institu\ntions now valiantly combatting distrust and rumor and\nsteering through the shoals to safety.\nOur banks are the foundations of the entire financial\nstructure of our community. When we lose our heads and\ndestroy them we have destroyed the very institutions\nthrough which the blood and sinews of our business life\nmust flow.\nThough the banks of Little Rock have not co-operated\nwith Organized Labor in the past as closely as we should\nhave liked\u2014we unhesitatingly urge every laboring man in\nLittle Rock and Arkansas to stand by, cut the hysteria,\nstop the rumors and co-operate In real and honest support\nof our banking institutions in this city and state. They are\nsound and will remain sound only as we believe in them in,\nj word and.deed.-. THE UNION LABOR BULLETIN\n13-Year-Old Miss- Wins\nHigh Tefe-Kee-No Award\nNADINE ROTHERMEL BRINGS HOME THE BACON!\nYouth will be served! It has al\nways been and will ever be. Last\nvcek one of the daughters of labor\ndistinguished hersgif and her youth\nby being adjudged the best essay\nist in your paper\u2019s \"Tele-Kee-No\n1 eiephone Punic\u201d feature. Noth\ning that we write can adequately\nexpress the joy that goes with pre\nsenting Miss Nadine Rothermel,\nroil Parker avenue. North Little\nPock, with the highest honors and\nthe $1.00 that goes with it. Her\nessay, that of sheer simplicity, is:\n\u201cListen-In\u201d to Nadine\n\u201cJlear Tele-Kee-No\u201d:\n\u201cI have been reading your puzzle\neach week and* I-enjoy\u2019 it very\nnotch. I am a girl 13 yearsjof age.\nI like to make out the puzzjea.that\nyou have in the Labor Bulletin. The\nfirst one is the'Little Rock Laun\ndry Company. They certainly do\nw ash the clothes clean. They wash\nthem and wash them. There -are\nfive different places to which you\nmay send your clothes but I have\ntold every one to send their clothes\nto the Little Rock Laundry, Third\nand Center streets. The other one\nwas 42 per cent (treater than in\n1919, according to the. Federal Re\nserve index. The 1928 production\nrst' ^as 22 per cent above that of\n1919.\n\"Since 1919, industrial activity\n(output) has been increasing, but\n\u25a0with the exception of 1920 employ\nrunt show s a decline. Greater out\nput is and has beat accomplished\nwith a diminishing number of\nworkers.\u201d\nThe appalling necessity for dras\ntic action within industry is dem\nonstrated by the figures, the two\nmain requirements being for a\nshortening of the work week and\na geenral and sweeping increase\nin wages, wiping out finally the\nlow wage standards of the great\nlow wage industries like textiles,\nKi;s\u00a3\u00b0 figsfie\nif. the beat place in town for sea\nfood and plate lunches. It is the\nNew Orleans Sea Food Cafe, if you\npass by please go in and get <i\ngrand plate lunch and be served\nright away. It is the cleanest place\nin Little Rock where you can get\nj real sea food and always fresh. I\nwill close hoping I win the $1.00\nand five tickets to the Arkansas\nTheater.\u2014Miss Nadine Rothermel,\nFhone 4*0695, 1100 Parker Street.\nNorth Little Rock, Ark/'\nWell, Nadine we are mailing you\nthe $1.00 but you will have to keep\nsending in such nice essays to earn\nthe tickets.\nOther outstanding meritorious\nessays (in the Tele-Kee-No editor's\nopinion) that were awarded Ar\nj kam-as Theater tickets in last\nweek\u2019s series wer econtributed by\nthe following in the order enum\nerated: Mrs. Karle Miller, 240''.\nPiae street; Mrs. Jimmie Hartley\nJr.. 4208 C street; Mrs. H. If.\nTharkrey, 1306 West Second\nstreet; Mrs. M. Williams, 9264\nWest Seventh street, and Miss\nAlva Larch, 2408 Oak street.\nfill I in the low wage category be\ncause of automatic machinery an<J\nthe employment of what is known\nas \"unskilled\u201d labor.\nThe United States Federal Re\nserve Board, having at its com\nmend perhaps more intimate infor\nmation as to industry than any,\nether institution, governmental or\notherwise, has laid before the na\ntion its dramtic showing of the\ngrowing efficiency of machinery\nand the sweeping wave of unem\nployment that can go hand in hand\nwith increasing production because\nof machinery.\nThe Federal Reserve Board's\nshowing substantiates to the limit\nevery showing made by organised\nlabor regarding displacement of\n\u00bb\u00aeff. by.' OJMfei*1?*/* A r\"\" fc,: a\n\u201cBut tor One Thing, There Would\nHave Been No Business Depression\u201d\nDeclares the Washington Post\nEditor's Note: Organtred labor has ul\nmaintained that higher wag*-* con\nstituted tha real ntid fundamental basts\ntor prosperity. Health, happiness, educa\ntion are not only the results\u2014but NE\nCESSITIES. Some ot our biggest corpor\nations. monopolistic concerns and indi\nviduals. have not. seemingly, br.-n inclined\no agree But the WASHINGTON POST,\nundoubtedly one of the most conservative\nnewspapers In the United States, u o \\v\ncom>8 forward In the a\u00ab-nlth of our de\npression, to agree with the principles lor\nwhich labor has made a resolute stnnd\nfor years\n'Had the worker received In 19?9 the\nsatin. share of his \u2018product that h- re\nceived in 1849. SO yeurs ago. the employer\nwould have been forced to put >5,000.000.\n000 more in his pay envelope and there\nVMuld have been no business depression.\"\nIt would be difficult to state the case\nmore clenr\u2019.y and It 1# ind. cd most prob\nable that the sagacious mmd will agree\nwith the editorial of this cotisrt vmtve\nWashing'on newspaper. These \"hard\nlimes\" uto not cauaed b<v \u2018wot Id condi\ntions\" as soma frightened politician:,\nwould have us believe, but rather from the\npointed fact that the American worker is\nnot securing his due share ot th\u00ab things\nhe produces. The cure for hard tunes\nrests upon the workers' Wag-;.\nBo admtrable in form and sub tance\nis the article that appeared in last Bun\nday a edition of the Post that the La\nbor Bulletin prints It In full as follows;\nCause of the Crash.\nOut of many diagnoses of the\nbusiness depression economists\nhave arrived at the conclusion th.it\nthe country produced in the years\nimmediately preceding the crash\nmore goods than Ilia public could\nconsume with its limited buying\npower. The resultant surplus be\ncame if drug on the market, and it\nwas necessary to curtail produc\ntion while the slack was being tuk\nen up.\nUntil now this has been mere\ntheory. But figures that have just\nbeen worked out by the Census lJu-\nreau sustain the theory beyond i\ndoubt. The fact that there was an\n\u201cover-production\u201d can no longer b*: j\nquestioned. 1\nBut why did a surplus of good*\nbring hard times when thousand*\nof people are in need of more\nclothes, better food and more sub\nstantial houses, as well as the con\n'tenlences and luxuries of life?\nThe reason reaches far back in\nto history. In 1849, according to\nfigures of the Census liureuu, the\nmanufacturing industries of the\nUnited States produced goods val\nued at approximately $1,000,000,\n000 and paid $236,755,000 in wages:\nSince that time both wages and\nthe value of products have in\ncreased enormously. In 1929 the\noutput of the manufacturing indus\ntries reached the highest point in\nhistory. Goods turned out by\nAmerican plants were valued at\n$68,000,000,000.\nHad industry paid the same pro\nportion of this return in wages us\nit did in 1849, wage earners would\nhave received an aggregate of $16,\n000,000,000. Instead, they were\npaid $11,271,116,000.\nMany factors such as the cost \u00ab>f\nmachinery and the greater ex\npenses of distribution, enter into\nthis comparison, but these figures\nare sufficient to contradict the\npopular belief that wages are high\nin America.\nOn the basis of productive ca\npacity American labor is cheap.\nA study of the increases in both\nwages and industry suggests thal\nth* working man is not yet receiv\ning his full share of the wealth he\nhelps to create.\nA glance at the more recent fig\nures is more convincing. During\n1927 wages amounted to $10,818,*\n802,000 arid the products of the\nmanufacturing industries were\nworth $62,718,347,000. Wages in\ncreased in the following two years\nby $422,214,000, in spite of the\nfact that fewer workmen were em\nployed. But during that same pe\nriod production was augmented to\nthe extent of $5,735,139,000.\nIn other words, labor registered\na gain of 3.8 per cent in its pur\nchasing power, while the output of\nindustry gained more than 9 per\ncent.\nIn the^e figures lies the story\nof the industrial depression. While\ngoods war# being turned out at a\npace never before equaled in his\ntory, th\u00ab buying power of the pub\nlie was making but small gains.\nWhen tne climax was reached in\nthe last months of 1929 a period of\nadversity' was inevitable because\nthe people did not have sufficient\nmoney to buy the surplus g-xida\nwhich they had produced.\nThis diagnosis having been sup\nported by inescapable facts, the\nremedy becomea a matter of apply\ning tht economic law which those\nfacts suggest. If the country is to\nK\u00ab on producing at the 1929 level,\nthe buying power of the peopld\nmust be increased\nConsuming power already exists,\nand it has no limitations. From\nthe long-range view, all that is\nnecessary to mak\u00ab it effective is t-j\ninctease the earning power of tho\nworkman's family.\nit is estimated that at Vast 8S\nper cent of ail goods picouced in\nAmerica must be consumed by\nthose families actually engaged in\nthe task of production, if a surplus\nis to be avoided. Mass production\non any other basis is impossible.\nhen the indutrial processes ars\n1 ceiled up by the use of machin\nery the inccni0 of working men\ntrust be sufficient to enuble them\nto consume the surplus*\nDuring tho period while surplus\ngoods were piling up huge divi\ndends were going to stockholders*\nHad some ol these extra profits\nbeen distributed to wage earners\nthe worst effects of the depres\nsion could have been avoided.\nCorporations feel obligated to swell\nthe dividends of their stockholders\nhut when they do so at tho ex\nP-'Tiso of their employes they briny\niri.saster upon themselves.\nTho so-called overproduction is\nl ieng corrected by depletion of ths\nsurplus and reduction of prices,\nI-ut the adjustment is complicated\nl>> unemployment and lack of con\nfidence, This method is costly in\nthe extreme, both to industry and\nIf the fundamental relation bc\nI tween wages and the output of jn\ndustry is impressed upon the coun\nj try by this sad experience, there\ni tie soma hope of avoiding eco\nnomic Mila anc} hollows in the fu\ntu ,<V\nR. I. FIREMEN\nELECT OFFICERS\nFOR THE YEAR\nBy Fred Barnes, Secretary\nChoctaw I.odge No, 051, Loco\nmotive Firemen und Knginemcn,\nof the Bock Island Railroad Com\nity* held their regular meeting in\nIho VV, O. W. hall, November 13,\n1JK10.\n'J he mating was called to order\n!,V Mr. F. Peaslec, president of\ntFat body vJi\nA general feeling of enthusiasm\npn vailed us this was election day,\nI \u00abil were anxious to know the\nj result of the voting.\nSeveral changes wero made, but\nit might ho stated that a few of\nthe dd officers had made such\ncommendable records, that they\nwere retained for the ensuing year.\nThe following officers were de\nclared elected; L. S. Peas lee, pres\ni 'ee; Boy Bang*, vice president;\nred Barnes, financial secretary\ntreasurer; J. J), Kngli.sh, R. O.\nFasteriy and O. F. Holliman, board\nof trustees; L. H. Brewer, dele\ngate; Fred Barnes, legislative rep\nresentative; F. W. Boggs, local or\nganizer; Or. J. P. Sheppard, med\nha! examiner, and L. 11. Brewer,\nlocal chairman.\nThe above named officers will ba\ninstalled at the next regular meet\ning, which will be Thursday, No\nvember 27.\nFred Barnes, who has been on\ntiie sick list for the past three\nweeks, is now back on duty, and\nexpects to render untiring effort in\nmaking the coining year one of the\nlast. He insists that all cooperate\nand work together for a better at\ntendance in the future, which will\nresult in a more successful year.\n0. R. T. MAN ELECTED\nBY 3 T(M MAJORITY\nJohn T. Owen, a member of the\nOrder of Railroad Telegrapher*\nemployed on the Kansas City\nSouthern, has been elected to tha\nI ouse of representatives of the Ar\nkansas legislature on the Demo#\ncl tic ticket by a majority of bet\nter than three to one.\nThis is Mr. Owen's second term,\nand he expects to sponsor an old\nage pension bill and a workmen'#\ncompensation law when the legis\nlature convenes in Januajy\u00ab\u2018\u00bb2","height":"21200","width":"17596"}}
